      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 7-month-old full-term female infant is brought in by her mother due to poor weight gain. The child exhibits failure to thrive, hypotonia, reduced muscle mass, and significant head lag upon physical examination. Laboratory tests reveal markedly elevated levels of lactate, pyruvate, and alanine, with a blood gas analysis showing a pH of 7.0. Despite treatment with thiamine, the infant&#39;s lactic acidosis does not improve. Based on the clinical and laboratory findings, what is the most likely diagnosis?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q7479458",
